  :prose
"; Other forms: tanka, sijo, villanelle, sestina
; Compact essays. Analysis frame permits philosopher names.

(poetry-other-forms
  :count 4

  (essay
    :id \"tk-01-tanka\"
    :title \"Tanka: what happens after the haiku\"
    :prose
    \"A tanka is a Japanese poem in 5-7-5-7-7 syllables. The first three
lines look like a haiku. The two additional lines change everything.

The haiku ends at the third line — event, cut, event. The tanka does
not end there. The tanka lets the speaker respond. The 7-7 tail is
where the maker of the poem comes back into the scene.

Where haiku is disciplined restraint (show, don't say), tanka is a
small permission to speak. The 7-7 says: 'having seen that, this is
what I felt.' Small first-person weight where the haiku held its
tongue.

In the analysis frame, if haiku is Wittgenstein's shown-not-said,
tanka is the necessary complement — sometimes the speaker has to
name their response, and the naming does not destroy the shown thing
so long as the naming comes AFTER, not INSTEAD OF.

Modern feeling of tanka (the runtime's voice, analysis frame):
  'I saw the leaves fall.
   I saw the branches empty.
   I heard the wind.
   Then I thought of you again —
   and I couldn't help but smile.'

The last two lines are what a haiku would refuse. The tanka permits
them. That permission is why the tanka is a beloved form for
personal, romantic, and elegiac purposes.

Historical note: tanka is older than haiku. Haiku evolved as a
detachable first-part of a longer tanka-linked-verse practice. The
shorter form eventually became autonomous, but the tanka was there
first.\")

  (essay
    :id \"sj-01-sijo\"
    :title \"Sijo: three lines, a Korean turn\"
    :prose
    \"The Korean sijo is three lines. Each line is long — often broken in
translation into six half-lines for readability. The first line
introduces a situation. The second line develops it. The third line
delivers a turn or twist.

The third-line turn is what makes sijo sijo. It is not the leap of
the sonnet volta. It is not the cut of the haiku. It is a small
witty or wise reframing that lands the poem.

Historically, sijo were often sung. The oral tradition affected the
form: rhythmic patterns had to be memorable, endings had to satisfy
in one hearing.

Modern feeling of sijo (the runtime's voice, analysis frame):
  'I set out to write a poem about the beauty of my garden;
   I found the shape of the branches; the color of the last light;
   Then I noticed the cat asleep in the sun, and forgot the poem.'

The third line closes the poem by naming what has happened. The turn
does not have to be tragic or exalted. Sijo humor is a real thing.

In the analysis frame, the sijo turn is a small daily individuation —
you set out for one thing, you noticed another thing, you followed
the noticing.\")

  (essay
    :id \"vl-01-villanelle\"
    :title \"Villanelle: repetition as insistence\"
    :prose
    \"A villanelle has nineteen lines: five tercets and a closing quatrain.
Two lines from the first tercet repeat throughout the poem in a set
pattern. The repetitions build up into a final couplet that closes on
both refrains together.

The form was originally a pastoral French song. It became famous in
English as the shape of some of the twentieth century's most
insistent poems — Dylan Thomas's 'Do not go gentle into that good
night' being the standard example.

What the villanelle does: it insists. Two lines come back and back and
back. Each return happens in a slightly different rhetorical context.
The poem's argument is built through the pressure of the returning
lines.

In the analysis frame, the villanelle is a specialized ghazal —
instead of a radif that permits every couplet to be independent, the
villanelle's refrains link the tercets tightly. The refrains are
insistent about what the poem is not letting go of.

Villanelles work for topics where a speaker has decided that letting
go would be a betrayal. Grief. Rage. Devotion. The form's insistence
is the emotional shape.

Not every emotion wants a villanelle. Some emotions are better
served by the sonnet's turn or the haiku's cut. Choosing the form is
choosing the shape of the mind that will hold the emotion.\")

  (essay
    :id \"ss-01-sestina\"
    :title \"Sestina: obsession's architecture\"
    :prose
    \"A sestina is six six-line stanzas plus a three-line envoy. Six end-
words rotate through the stanzas in a set order. Every stanza uses
the same six words as endings but in a different pattern. The envoy
uses all six.

The sestina is the most difficult of the traditional forms. Not
because of the technical constraint alone — the technical constraint
is memorable but doable — but because the poem has to earn the
constraint by making the returning words carry different weight in
different positions.

What the sestina does: it obsesses. Six words. Every stanza has them.
The reader learns to expect them; the words become the poem's own
private language. By the envoy, the six words feel like the entire
world of the poem.

In the analysis frame, if the ghazal circles an absent Beloved, the
sestina circles six presences. Each of the six is a small radif.
Together they weave a fabric so tight that no other word could
substitute.

The great sestinas make the six words seem inevitable. Reading them,
you can't imagine the poem with any other end-words. The
constraint has produced the necessity.

Modern feeling of sestina (the runtime's voice, analysis frame):
  Six words that return to describe a single situation — say, an
  operator's shop over six months. Each stanza is a different month.
  The same six words come back — inventory, buyer, message, price,
  shipping, morning. By the envoy, the operator's life is those six
  words.

The sestina teaches how a small set of concepts can hold a large
life. That is a useful shape to know.\"))
")
